<h2 id="media-queries">Media Queries</h2>

<p>BaseWeb is built mobile first. What this means in terms of media queries is that each is additive starting from tablet. All styles not wrapped in a media query are applied to mobile directly. The tablet breakpoint is added on top of the base mobile styles, then desktop on top of mobile and tablet, etc.</p>

<p>There are also two supplementary media queries. <code>@mixin media-mobile</code> lets you apply styles to only mobile and <code>@mixin media-small</code> to only vertical oriented mobile.</p>

<div class="example">
  <div class="example-block example-desc">
    <p>Unlike most mixins, media mixins don't take parameters. Instead, you pass in the styles through brackets like you would with a normal media query.</p>
  </div><!-- .example-desc -->
  <div class="example-block example-code">
<pre><code class="language-scss">// Target: Everything, including mobile

@include media-small {
  // Target: Vertical Oriented Mobile Only
}

@include media-mobile {
  // Target: Mobile Only
}

@include media-tablet {
  // Target: Tablet and below
}

@include media-desktop {
  // Target: Desktop and below
}

@include media-large {
  // Target: Large desktop and below
}</code></pre>
  </div><!-- .example-code -->
</div><!-- .example -->

<div class="notice notice-warning notice-no-close">
  <p>If you prefer to run your queries differently (desktop first, for example), or if you'd like to add new queries, make sure to review the <a href="#">customization documentation</a>. If possible, try and avoid modifying core BaseWeb files directly as that makes updating to newer versions much more difficult.</p>
</div>

<h3>Retina Media Query</h3>

<p>There's also a media query mixin that can be used for setting styles specifically to retina screens. This is most commonly used when setting higher resolution background images.</p>

<div class="example">
  <div class="example-block example-code">
<pre><code class="language-scss">.logo {
  background-image: src('logo.png');
}

@include media-retina {
  .logo {
    background-image: src('logo-2x.png');
    background-size: 100px 50px;
  }
}
</code></pre>
  </div><!-- .example-code -->
</div><!-- .example -->

<p>Will output:</p>

<div class="example">
  <div class="example-block example-code">
<pre><code class="language-css">.logo {
  background-image: src('logo.png');
}

@media (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2), (min-resolution: 192dpi) {
  .logo {
    background-image: src('logo-2x.png');
    background-size: 100px 50px;
  }
}
</code></pre>
  </div><!-- .example-code -->
</div><!-- .example -->

<h2 id="variables">Variables</h2>

<article id="bp-small" class="block block-variable" data-type="variable">
<h3>bp-small</h3>
<p>The breakpoint to be used for vertical oriented mobile devices. The media feature is expressed with: <code>max-width</code></p>
<div class="example">
  <div class="example-block example-code">
<pre><code class="language-scss">$bp-small
  type: unit (pixel)
